   "source": [
    "# Differential Expression and Random Forest Classification of Lung Cancer vs. Pulmonary Infection from BALF RNA-seq Data\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Transcriptome-Based Classification of Lung Cancer and Pulmonary Infection via PyDESeq2 and Random Forest\n",
    "\n",
    "![image.png](attachment:6485c3d1-949a-496c-9300-4c31ed7de4e0.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "06454460-9144-4d50-bbfb-d75bb0d150e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Introduction\n",
    "Distinguishing lung cancer from pulmonary infections remains a persistent clinical challenge, as both conditions can present with overlapping radiological and symptomatic profiles, leading to delayed or missed diagnoses.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook applies a computational transcriptomics approach to publicly available BALF RNA-seq data from GSE252118, a prospective cohort study comparing lung cancer and pulmonary infection patients. Using PyDESeq2 — a Python implementation of the widely adopted DESeq2 negative binomial model — we identify differentially expressed host genes between conditions, then leverage those signatures as features in a Random Forest classification model.\n",
    "\n",
    "The analysis proceeds through the following stages:\n",
    "\n",
    "##### 1. Data loading and preprocessing — raw count filtering, metadata alignment, and AnnData construction\n",
    "##### 2. Differential expression analysis — dispersion estimation, LFC shrinkage, and significance filtering via Wald test\n",
    "##### 3. Dimensionality reduction — PCA, UMAP, and Leiden clustering on significant genes\n",
    "##### 4. Visualization — heatmap with hierarchical clustering and volcano plot\n",
    "##### 5. Machine learning classification — Random Forest training, hyperparameter tuning, and model evaluation\n",
    "##### 6. Feature interpretation — built-in and permutation-based feature importance, co-expression structure of top predictive genes\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "This work demonstrates how host gene expression signatures derived from BALF can serve as interpretable, biologically grounded features for distinguishing cancer from infection — complementing broader multi-modal mNGS approaches and supporting the case for transcriptomics as a component of non-invasive lung cancer diagnostics.\n"
   ]
