    "In this first analysis, we ignore the group variable and use the condition column as our design factor. That is, we compare gene expressions of samples that have condition B to those that have condition A.\n",
    "\n",
    "Read counts modeling with the DeseqDataSet class\n",
    "We start by creating a DeseqDataSet object from the count and metadata data. A DeseqDataSet fits dispersion and log-fold change (LFC) parameters from the data, and stores them.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "00906779-54ff-4e5e-a7ca-74b659131de9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Create an Adata object\n",
    "\n",
    "The adata object is an instance of the AnnData class from the anndata Python package. It's a powerful and flexible data structure designed for storing annotated data matrices, especially in bioinformatics and single-cell genomics—but it's also useful for bulk RNA-seq data like you're working with.\n",
    "\n",
    "AnnData is a container that holds:\n",
    "\n",
    "A data matrix (e.g., gene expression counts)\n",
    "Annotations for rows (samples or cells)\n",
    "Annotations for columns (genes or features)\n",
    "Optional layers, metadata, and more"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "id": "24bf4c85-9995-4c42-bab7-acb4c7aff830",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#Create an adata object\n",
    "adata = anndata.AnnData(\n",
    "    X=counts_df.values,\n",
    "    obs=metadata,\n",
    "    var=pd.DataFrame(index=counts_df.columns)\n",
    ")"
   ]
